            <!-- Task 1: House Cup -->
            <div id="task1" class="tab-pane">
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Task 1: The House Cup Championship</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4">The bar chart below shows the final House Cup points for the four Hogwarts houses over a three-year period, from 1991 to 1993. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.</p>
                        <div class="chart-container">
                            <canvas id="houseCupChart"></canvas>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="prose max-w-none">
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Band 9 Model Answer</h3>
                        <p>The provided bar chart <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">illustrates</span> the total points awarded to the four Hogwarts houses—Gryffindor, Slytherin, Hufflepuff, and Ravenclaw—at the conclusion of the academic years 1991, 1992, and 1993.</p>
                        <p><span class="slytherin-green">Overall, Slytherin consistently achieved the highest scores in all three years, though Gryffindor experienced the most dramatic increase in points to become a close competitor by 1993. Hufflepuff and Ravenclaw, in contrast, remained in the lower ranks with relatively stable scores throughout the period.</span></p>
                        <p><span class="gryffindor-red">Looking at the details,</span> Slytherin began in a <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">dominant</span> position in 1991 with approximately 472 points, the highest total recorded. <span class="ravenclaw-blue">While their score saw a marginal decline to 468 in 1992, it recovered slightly to 470 in 1993, ensuring they remained the top-scoring house.</span> <span class="gryffindor-red">Meanwhile,</span> Gryffindor's performance was far more <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">volatile</span>. Starting at just 312 points in 1991, their total <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">surged</span> to 462 in 1992, before reaching 470 points in 1993, <span class="ravenclaw-blue">a figure identical to Slytherin's final score in that year.</span></p>
                        <p><span class="gryffindor-red">In stark contrast,</span> the other two houses showed little change. Ravenclaw's points <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">hovered</span> between 426 and 430. <span class="ravenclaw-blue">Similarly, Hufflepuff consistently scored the lowest among the four, with their points total remaining just above the 350-point mark across all three years.</span></p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Task 2: Demographics -->
            <div id="task2" class="tab-pane hidden">
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Task 2: Hogwarts Student Demographics</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4">The line graph below shows the percentage of students at Hogwarts from three different backgrounds (Pure-blood, Half-blood, and Muggle-born) between 1970 and 2000. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.</p>
                        <div class="chart-container">
                            <canvas id="demographicsChart"></canvas>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="prose max-w-none">
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Band 9 Model Answer</h3>
                        <p>The line graph <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">delineates</span> the changes in the proportional representation of Pure-blood, Half-blood, and Muggle-born students at Hogwarts over a 30-year timeframe, from 1970 to 2000.</p>
                        <p><span class="slytherin-green">Overall, the percentage of Half-blood students rose significantly to become the dominant group, while the proportion of Pure-blood students witnessed a steady decline. The representation of Muggle-borns, however, remained relatively low and stable throughout the entire period.</span></p>
                        <p><span class="gryffindor-red">Initially,</span> in 1970, Pure-blood students constituted the largest group, at precisely 60% of the student body. <span class="ravenclaw-blue">However, this figure experienced a consistent and considerable fall, eventually dropping to just 25% by the year 2000.</span> <span class="gryffindor-red">Conversely,</span> the percentage of Half-blood students began at a modest 25% but followed a <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">sharp upward trend.</span> It overtook the Pure-blood line around 1985 and continued to climb, <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">culminating</span> at 60% in 2000, effectively swapping places with the Pure-blood demographic.</p>
                        <p><span class="gryffindor-red">Meanwhile,</span> the proportion of Muggle-born students was the smallest and least variable. <span class="ravenclaw-blue">Starting at 15% in 1970, their representation saw only minor fluctuations over the subsequent three decades, ending at the slightly lower figure of 15% in 2000.</span> This indicates they remained a consistent minority within the Hogwarts population.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Task 3: Owl Post -->
            <div id="task3" class="tab-pane hidden">
                 <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                    <div>
                        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Task 3: The Owl Post Delivery System</h2>
                        <p class="mb-4">The diagram below illustrates the process by which owls deliver mail in the wizarding world. Summarise the information by selecting and reporting the main features, and make comparisons where relevant.</p>
                        <div class="w-full p-4 bg-gray-50 rounded-lg">
                           <div class="flex flex-col space-y-2">
                                <div class="flex items-center">
                                    <div class="process-step">1. Attach Mail</div>
                                    <div class="process-arrow self-center mx-2">→</div>
                                    <div class="process-step">2. Give Recipient Name</div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-end"><span class="process-arrow transform -rotate-90">→</span></div>
                                 <div class="flex items-center">
                                    <div class="process-step">4. Mail Detached</div>
                                    <div class="process-arrow self-center mx-2">←</div>
                                    <div class="process-step">3. Owl Undertakes Journey</div>
                                </div>
                                <div class="flex justify-start"><span class="process-arrow transform -rotate-90">→</span></div>
                                <div class="flex items-center">
                                    <div class="process-step">5. Owl Receives Treat</div>
                                    <div class="process-arrow self-center mx-2">→</div>
                                    <div class="process-step">6. Return to Owlery</div>
                                </div>
                                 <div class="flex justify-center"><span class="process-arrow transform -rotate-90">→</span></div>
                                 <div class="process-step w-1/2 mx-auto">7. Rest & Await Next Task</div>
                           </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="prose max-w-none">
                        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Band 9 Model Answer</h3>
                        <p>The provided diagram <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">outlines</span> the cyclical, multi-stage process of mail delivery via owls.</p>
                        <p><span class="slytherin-green">Overall, the process is a linear sequence involving seven key stages, beginning with the sender attaching a letter to an owl and concluding with the owl returning to its home at the Owlery to await the next task.</span></p>
                        <p>The delivery cycle <span class="hufflepuff-yellow">commences</span> when a witch or wizard fastens a letter or parcel securely to an owl's leg. <span class="gryffindor-red">Following this,</span> the owl is given the recipient's name, which is the sole instruction required for navigation. <span class="ravenclaw-blue">Once dispatched, the third stage involves the owl undertaking its journey, which can span any distance to locate the intended person.</span></p>
                        <p><span class="gryffindor-red">Upon arrival,</span> the owl presents the mail to the recipient, who then detaches it. <span class="ravenclaw-blue">Subsequently, it is customary for the recipient to provide the owl with a treat and water as a reward for its service.</span> The penultimate stage is the owl's return flight to its home Owlery. <span class="gryffindor-red">Finally,</span> the owl rests and recuperates in the Owlery, thereby completing the cycle and making itself available for future deliveries.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
